§ 12109. Payments for incarceration on tribal lands(a) Reservation of fundsNotwithstanding any other provision of this part, of amounts made available to the Attorney General to carry out programs relating to offender incarceration, the Attorney General shall reserve $35,000,000 for each of fiscal years 2011 through 2015 to carry out this section.


(b) Grants to Indian tribes(1) In generalFrom the amounts reserved under subsection (a), the Attorney General shall provide grants—(A) to Indian tribes for purposes of—(i) construction and maintenance of jails on Indian land for the incarceration of offenders subject to tribal jurisdiction;

(ii) entering into contracts with private entities to increase the efficiency of the construction of tribal jails; and

(iii) developing and implementing alternatives to incarceration in tribal jails;


(B) to Indian tribes for the construction of tribal justice centers that combine tribal police, courts, and corrections services to address violations of tribal civil and criminal laws;

(C) to consortia of Indian tribes for purposes of constructing and operating regional detention centers on Indian land for long-term incarceration of offenders subject to tribal jurisdiction, as the applicable consortium determines to be appropriate.


(2) Priority of fundingin 11 So in original. Probably should be capitalized. providing grants under this subsection, the Attorney General shall take into consideration applicable—(A) reservation crime rates;

(B) annual tribal court convictions; and

(C) bed space needs.


(3) Federal shareBecause of the Federal nature and responsibility for providing public safety on Indian land, the Federal share of the cost of any activity carried out using a grant under this subsection shall be 100 percent.



